    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What should I look for when choosing a sleep product?</summary>
        <p>Focus on the specific sleep problem you're trying to solve: light sensitivity (sleep masks), body temperature (weighted blankets), racing thoughts (white noise), or quality of sleep (supplements). The best product is one that targets your actual pain point, not the most hyped option.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are weighted blankets really worth it?</summary>
        <p>Yes — if you have anxiety or have trouble falling asleep. Weighted blankets provide deep pressure stimulation that activates the parasympathetic nervous system, similar to a hug. Start with a blanket that's 8-10% of your body weight. Not everyone benefits equally, but many sleep-anxious people see measurable improvement in sleep latency.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Do sleep masks actually block light?</summary>
        <p>Quality sleep masks block 95%+ of light. Look for contoured designs that don't press on your eyelids (which can cause discomfort) and adjustable straps that prevent light leakage from the sides. Blackout rooms aren't always possible, so a good sleep mask is a worthwhile backup.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Is mouth tape safe to use while sleeping?</summary>
        <p>Yes — when used correctly with proper nasal breathing. Mouth tape is designed to seal the mouth gently (not restrict breathing) and encourage nasal breathing, which improves oxygen absorption and reduces snoring. Start with a half-hour during the day to adapt, then gradually extend nightly use. People with sleep apnea should consult a doctor first.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What's the difference between melatonin gummies and capsules?</summary>
        <p>Gummies are easier to take and often taste better, but capsules provide more consistent dosing and absorption. Gummies can stick to teeth and are less precise for microdosing. For sleep, 0.5-3mg is typically effective; higher doses don't always work better. Start low and adjust based on your response.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How long does it take for sleep supplements to work?</summary>
        <p>Melatonin typically takes 20-40 minutes and peaks around 1 hour. Most people notice effects within 3-5 nights of consistent use. Sleep is highly individualized — some people see results immediately, others need 2 weeks. Track your sleep quality for at least 7 days before deciding if something works for you.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What's the best white noise machine for sleep?</summary>
        <p>Look for machines with fan noise or brown noise (deeper than white noise) rather than bird sounds or rain, which have variable volume that can jolt you awake. Consistency matters more than realism. A good sleep machine should have a timer, volume control, and ideally a backup battery or be on backup power.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can sleep masks with Bluetooth actually help you fall asleep?</summary>
        <p>Yes — if you fall asleep to podcasts, audiobooks, or white noise. Bluetooth sleep masks eliminate earbud pressure and tangles while maintaining light blockage. The key is using one designed for side sleepers with flat speakers that don't dig into your head, not domed ear cups.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Should I buy a sleep product bundle or individual items?</summary>
        <p>Individual items let you tailor your sleep routine to your specific needs. Bundles make sense if you're buying multiple products you actually need, but avoid bundling items you won't use. Test one category at a time (light blocking first, then temperature, then supplements) to isolate what actually helps you.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How often should I update or replace my sleep products?</summary>
        <p>Sleep masks and straps should be replaced every 12-18 months as materials degrade. Weighted blankets last 3-5 years with proper care (wash in cool water, air dry). Sleep supplements need no replacement as long as they're stored in a cool, dry place. White noise machines last indefinitely.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

